Below are the steps for a successful integration.

## Getting Started

Here is how to get started using the ShipBob API.

### 1. Create sandbox account on ShipBob

* Sign up link: [https://webstage.shipbob.dev/app/merchant/#/SignUp](https://webstage.shipbob.dev/app/merchant/#/SignUp)

* Our sandbox accounts are separate from production. I recommend bookmarking the sign up page to not conflict with production account.

### 2. Generate a PAT token

Before making your first API request with ShipBob you need to generate a PAT token. On the ShipBob dashboard go to Integrations > API Tokens and generate token.
*Note: We recommend using the PAT token to get started using the ShipBob API. You will eventually have to create Oauth2 credentials by registering your application by filling out* [*this form*](https://forms.office.com/r/AYx81v67MD)*. Learn more about our* [*auth*](https://developer.shipbob.com/auth/)*.*

### 3. Make your first API request

Make a request to the ShipBob API at our [GET channels endpoint](https://developer.shipbob.com/api-docs/#tag/Channels/paths/~11.0~1channel/get) to get your channel ID using Bearer and PAT token you generated in step 2. The channel name will be labeled something like this: “Privileged Access Token Monday, May 6, 2024”. For example, the channel ID in the screenshot below is 67292.

To make POST requests in the future I will have to pass `shipbob_channel_id: 67292` in the header to create products, orders, returns, and more for this specific channel.

## Create Products

When creating products in ShipBob using PoweredBy you need to pass the `reference_id` in ShipBob with the value of the merchant\_id pipe separated with the sku value in your system. For example, let’s say the merchant\_id in your system is 733066 and you want to create a new product in ShipBob with the sku as BLUE-T-SHIRT. Here is how you would create a product in ShipBob:


POST [https://sandbox-api.shipbob.com/1.0/product](https://sandbox-api.shipbob.com/1.0/product)
Headers: shipbob\_channel\_id: 733066

\{
&#x20;   "reference\_id": "733066 | BLUE-T-SHIRT",
&#x20;   "sku": "BLUE-T-SHIRT",
&#x20;   "name": "Blue T-Shirt"
}

![shot-Insomnia-002810@2x.png](data:image/png;base64,)![shot-Insomnia-002813@2x.png](data:image/png;base64,)

## Create Orders

Similar to creating products, you will need to do something similar for creating orders but this time we need to pipe separate the merchant\_id with the order\_number. For example, the merchant\_id in your system is 73306, the order id is 00100001 and you want to create an order for 1 Blue T-Shirt. Here is how you would create a order:


POST [https://sandbox-api.shipbob.com/1.0/order](https://sandbox-api.shipbob.com/1.0/order)
Headers: shipbob\_channel\_id: 733066
\{
&#x20;   "shipping\_method": "Free 2-day Shipping",
&#x20;   "recipient": \{
&#x20;       "name": "John Doe",
&#x20;       "address": \{
&#x20;               "address1": "100 Nowhere Blvd",
&#x20;               "address2": "Suite 100",
&#x20;               "city": "Gotham City",
&#x20;               "state": "NJ",
&#x20;               "country": "US",
&#x20;               "zip\_code": "07093"
&#x20;       },
&#x20;       "email": "john@example.com",
&#x20;       "phone\_number": "555-555-5555"
&#x20;   },
&#x20;   "products": \[
&#x20;       \{
&#x20;               "reference\_id": "733066 | BLUE-T-SHIRT",
&#x20;               "name": "Blue T-Shirt",
&#x20;               "quantity": 1
&#x20;       }
&#x20;   ],
&#x20;   "reference\_id": "00100001",
&#x20;   "order\_number": "733066 | 00100001",
&#x20;   "type": "DTC",
&#x20;   "purchase\_date": "2024-04-30T11:15:22Z",
&#x20;   "financials": \{
&#x20;       "total\_price": 25.57
&#x20;   }
}

## Create Channel

Every time you onboard a new merchant for your ShipBob PoweredBy integration you need to create a new channel. Best practice is to pass the merchant\_id in your system as the channel name in ShipBob. For example, if the merchant\_id or account\_id in your system is 733066, create a new channel with the name as 733066. When you only want to make requests for merchant 733066 in the future you can specify by passing the `shipbob_channel_id` in the header.
**How to create channel?**


* Create a new channel by making a POST request: [https://sandbox-api.shipbob.com/2.0/channel](https://sandbox-api.shipbob.com/2.0/channel). For production accounts it will be [https://api.shipbob.com/2.0/channel](https://api.shipbob.com/2.0/channel)

*Note: Before making this request you need to reach out to ShipBob and ask them to add the `channels_create` scope to your application. Reach out to us via Slack or email Nick Stoicof (*[*nstoicof@shipbob.com*](mailto:nstoicof@shipbob.com)*), Manisha Taparia (*[*mtaparia@shipbob.com*](mailto:mtaparia@shipbob.com)*), and Simon Gondeck (*[*sgondeck@shipbob.com*](mailto:sgondeck@shipbob.com)*).*
![shot-Postman-002807@2x.png](data:image/png;base64,)Going forward you will have to pass the `shipbob_channel_id` when you want to create products, orders, returns and more for this specific merchant. In addition, to only fetch products or orders for merchant 733066, you can simply pass the `shipbob_channel_id` in the header of your GET requests.


`curl --location '`[https://sandbox-api.shipbob.com/2.0/channel](https://sandbox-api.shipbob.com/2.0/channel)`' \ --header 'Accept: application/json' \ --header 'Content-Type: application/json' \ --header 'Authorization: bearer <token>' \ --data '{ "name":"TestChannel" }'`

## Sync tracking

The easiest way to sync tracking details from ShipBob to your system is by subscribing to our webhooks. For example, subscribe to our `order_shipped` webhook by making a POST request to our Create Webhook endpoint here: [https://sandbox-api.shipbob.com/1.0/webhook](https://sandbox-api.shipbob.com/1.0/webhook) or [https://api.shipbob.com/1.0/webhook](https://api.shipbob.com/1.0/webhook) for production. Below is a sample request (make sure to update the subscription url to the url where you will be listening to events):


POST [https://sandbox-api.shipbob.com/1.0/webhook](https://sandbox-api.shipbob.com/1.0/webhook)
\{
&#x20;   "topic": "order\_shipped",
&#x20;   "subscription\_url": "[https://examplewebhookurl.com/xyz](https://examplewebhookurl.com/xyz)"
}

* Listen to the webhook url. When an order is shipped, the webhook payload sends. Iterate through each shipment in the shipments array. Associate the `reference_id` in each shipment to the order id in your system. Sync the tracking\_number in the tracking array to pass tracking details when creating shipment event in your system.

* Good to know: you can create either 1 webhook for order\_shipped and use across all your merchants as the webhook payload will specify the channel ID in each request. You could also create 1 webhook for each channel/merchant if that’s what you prefer to do.

## Sync inventory

See the bottom of our Guides page: [https://developer.shipbob.com/guides/](https://developer.shipbob.com/guides/)


### Multiple locations

If you integration will support your merchants using multiple ShipBob fulfillment centers (i.e. Chicago, Los Angeles, Toronto and London), then you need to do the following:


* Get products: [https://developer.shipbob.com/api-docs/#tag/Products/paths/\~11.0\~1product/get](https://developer.shipbob.com/api-docs/#tag/Products/paths/~11.0~1product/get)

  * Iterate through the `fulfillable_quantity_by_fulfillment_center` array to get inventory quantities at each location. Best practice is to sync the `fulfillable_quantity` back to your system.

* Get inventory item: [https://api.shipbob.com/1.0/inventory](https://developer.shipbob.com/api-docs/#tag/Inventory/paths/~11.0~1inventory~1%7BinventoryId%7D/get)

  * Iterate through the `fulfillable_quantity_by_fulfillment_center` array to get inventory quantities at each location. Best practice is to sync the `fulfillable_quantity` back to your system.
